				\begin{document}$${P}_{{{{\mathrm{GP}}}}}=43.{1}_{-2.6}^{+2.8}$$\end{document} days. These results suggest that the signal has low harmonic complexity and that the rotation period of the star is close to 43 days, in agreement with the periodogram analysis of the RV measurements and activity indicators and the results obtained with the Super-WASP photometry. The low harmonic complexity of the process describing the stellar signal in the activity indicators suggests that the stellar signal in the RVs has a relatively low harmonic complexity too, and a quasi-sinusoidal behaviour (see ref. 96 for more details).

